{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488746"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:54:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:54:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"523"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/523"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.02,0.8,0.06,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54077"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/523"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39552"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1717"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8869"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"142"},{"type":"contributions","id":"247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6330"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16329"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43968"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54077"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of sudden, severe blurring of vision in his right eye. He denies any pain in the eye. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed 15 years ago and hypertension. His regular medications include metformin and perindopril. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history and drinks four standard drinks of alcohol daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 160/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There are carotid bruits audible on auscultation bilaterally. There is absence of the right direct pupillary reflex and left consensual pupillary reflex. Visual acuity is 6/18 in the left eye, but restricted to hand movements at one metre in the right eye. Fundoscopy is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute angle-closure glaucoma","Age-related macular degeneration","Central retinal artery occlusion","Diabetic retinopathy","Hypertensive retinopathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is typical of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral retinal artery occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E (CRAO), which classically presents with sudden, severe, painless visual loss, a relative afferent pupillary defect, and a \u0022cherry-red spot\u0022 seen on fundoscopy. The fundoscopic image shows retinal whitening (indicating ischaemia) with sparing of the fovea, giving the characteristic cherry-red spot appearance. CRAO is most commonly caused by an embolus originating from an atherosclerotic carotid artery, which is supported by the presence of carotid bruits in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute angle-closure glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an important cause of sudden visual loss to consider. However, it is typically accompanied by severe eye pain, headache, nausea, and vomiting. The findings on examination are seen in the anterior chamber (cloudy cornea, shallow anterior chamber, mid-dilated unreactive pupil) rather than on the fundus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge-related macular degeneration\u003C/strong\u003E does not present with sudden visual loss. It is a chronic process, with visual degeneration typically beginning in the centre of the visual field. The fundoscopic appearance would show drusen or geographic atrophy in dry AMD, or subretinal haemorrhage or fluid in wet AMD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic condition that develops over years. While it can cause sudden vision loss due to vitreous haemorrhage or tractional retinal detachment, the fundoscopic appearance would show microaneurysms, dot and blot haemorrhages, cotton wool spots, and potentially neovascularisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertensive retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is also a chronic condition and is unlikely to cause such sudden, severe, unilateral vision loss. The fundoscopic appearance would typically show arteriolar narrowing, arteriovenous nicking, flame-shaped haemorrhages, and cotton wool spots.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf note, there appears to be an island of normally perfused retina adjacent to the inferior temporal edge of the optic disc. This is likely due to the presence of a cilio-retinal artery, an anatomic variant that can preserve a small island of vision in CRAO. This patient requires urgent evaluation for carotid endarterectomy, as many patients with CRAO are at risk of recurrent events or other cerebrovascular accidents unless they undergo revascularisation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Central retinal artery occlusion (CRAO) typically presents with sudden, painless vision loss and a cherry-red spot on fundoscopy.","CRAO is a well-recognised complication of carotid artery disease and requires urgent evaluation for carotid endarterectomy.","The presence of a cilio-retinal artery can preserve a small island of vision in CRAO."],"references":["Hayreh SS, Podhajsky PA, Zimmerman MB. Retinal artery occlusion: associated systemic and ophthalmic abnormalities. Ophthalmology. 2009 Oct;116(10):1928-36. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19577305/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39552"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"523"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20182"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20182"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/439e8e25-8962-491f-85c2-67a4a4c58c42.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/439e8e25-8962-491f-85c2-67a4a4c58c42.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":545,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39552"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-30T08:56:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-30T08:57:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"523"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54077"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/